                <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
                <p>The clinical evidence is clear: PRP does increase hair density, and it does so through well-understood biological mechanisms. Multiple randomized controlled trials and meta-analyses have demonstrated statistically significant density improvements of 20-40 percent in patients with early to moderate hair loss. PRP works by reactivating dormant follicles, reversing miniaturization, enhancing blood supply, and prolonging the growth phase -- all of which contribute to a measurable increase in the number and quality of hairs per square centimeter.</p>
                <p>The best results come from a complete treatment course of 4-6 initial sessions followed by regular maintenance, ideally combined with complementary therapies like microneedling or minoxidil. Factors like overall health, nutrition, lifestyle, and the stage of hair loss all influence the degree of improvement, but for the right candidate, PRP offers a safe, clinically validated path to meaningfully denser hair.</p>
